\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the various processes of analysis there are certain classes of functions
 which ocur with remarkable frequency.
 Of these there are some which have been studied with great care, and of
 which general theories have been developed.
 The functions known as 
\emph on
determinants
\emph default
 constitute such a class, and one which is of great importance in some of
 the modern developments of mathematics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the simplest of the many processes giving rise to determinants, and
 that which led Leibnitz in 1693 to their discovery, is the solution of
 systems of simultaneous equations of the first degree.
 His researches in this subject resulted in the statement of some rather
 clumsy rules for eliminating the unknowns from systems of linear equations,
 and exerted no influence whatever upon subsequent investigations in the
 same direction.
 It was over a half century later, in 1750, that Gabriel Cramer first formulated
 an intelligible and general definition of the functions, based upon the
 recognition of the two classes of permutations, as presently to be set
 forth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Though Cramer failed to recognize, even to the same extent as Leibnitz,
 the importance of the functions thus defined, the development of the subject
 from this time on has been almost continuous and often rapid.
 The name ``determinant'' is due to Gauss, who, with Vandermonde, Lagrange,
 Cauchy, Jacobi, and others, ranks among the great pioneers in this development.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the subsequent years the theory of determinants has come into very general
 use, and has, in the hands of such mathematicians as Cayley and Sylvester,
 led to the results of the greatest interest and importance, both through
 the study of special form of the functions themselves and through their
 applications.
