\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 upon something like Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:8"

\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 merely permutes the permutations that index the terms.
 Put another way, there is a one-to-one correspondence between permutations
 in general and permutations composed with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Similar reasoning holds for Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1.6.2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1.6.3"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We summarize some of the most basic properties of the determinant below.
 The proof of the following theorem uses properties of permutations, properties
 of the sign function on permutations, and properties of sums over the symmetric
 group.
 In thinking about these properties, it is useful to keep in mind that,
 using Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:8"

\end_inset

, the determinant of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the sum over all possible ways of selecting 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, where exactly one element is selected from each row and from each column
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Thm:Properties-of-Det"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be a positive integer, and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(a_{ij}\right)\in\mathbb{F}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(0_{n\times n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(I_{n}\right)=1,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0_{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 zero matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A determinant is a linear homogeneous function of the elements of any row
 or column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If all the elements of a row (column) are equal to zero, then the determinant
 is equal to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is upper or lower triangular the 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is equal to the product of the diagonal elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The value of a determinant does not change when its rows and columns are
 interchanged i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(A^{T}\right)=\det\left(A\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The value of the determinant changes sign when two rows are interchanged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The value of the determinant changes sign when two columns are interchanged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A determinant with two identical rows (columns) equals zero if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 does not have characteristic 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given any other matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathbb{F}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(AB\right)=\det\left(A\right)\det\left(B\right).
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The first four properties follow directly from the definition of the determinant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
That 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(0_{n\times n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 is obvious and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(I_{n}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 follows because only the identity permutation contributes to the sum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Referring to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:8"

\end_inset

, we see that each term of the sum in the right-hand side contains as a
 factor one and only one element from every row and every column.
 Therefore a determinant is a linear homogeneous function of the elements
 of any row or column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Again this is obvious from the definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular.
 Then there is only one non-zero term in the sum on the rhs of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:8"

\end_inset

 viz., chose 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{11}$
\end_inset

 from the first row and first column, chose 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{22}$
\end_inset

 from the second row and second column and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

 are obtained from those of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by interchanging the row and column indices, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A^{T}\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(A^{T}\right)=\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)a_{\pi\left(1\right)1}a_{\pi\left(2\right)2}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{\pi\left(n\right)n}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the commutativity of the product in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sgn\left(\pi^{-1}\right)=\sgn\left(\pi\right)$
\end_inset

, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(A^{T}\right) & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi^{-1}\right)a_{1\pi^{-1}\left(1\right)}a_{2\pi^{-1}\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\pi^{-1}\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)a_{1\pi\left(1\right)}a_{2\pi\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \det\left(A\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be the matrix obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by interchanging the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th rows.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(B\right) & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)b_{1\pi\left(1\right)}b_{2\pi\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{i\pi\left(i\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{j\pi\left(j\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{n\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)a_{1\pi\left(1\right)}a_{2\pi\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{j\pi\left(i\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{i\pi\left(j\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\pi\left(n\right).}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\left(i\, j\right)$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\pi\tau\right)\left(k\right)=\begin{cases}
\pi\left(j\right) & \textrm{if }k=i\\
\pi\left(i\right) & \textrm{if }k=j\\
\pi\left(k\right) & \textrm{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(B\right) & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\tau\right)a_{1\pi\tau\left(1\right)}a_{2\pi\tau\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{j\pi\tau\left(i\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{i\pi\tau\left(j\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\pi\tau\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & -\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)a_{1\pi\left(1\right)}a_{2\pi\left(2\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{j\pi\left(j\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{i\pi\left(i\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & -\det\left(A\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Follows from (5) and (6).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If a determinant has two identical rows and we interchange them, then on
 the one hand we change nothing, while on the other hand, according to what
 has been proved, we change the sign of the determinant.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=-\det\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $2\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 if the field characteristic is not 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the standard expression for the matrix entries of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

 in terms of the matrix entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(a_{ij}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(b_{ij}\right),$
\end_inset

 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(AB\right) & = & \sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)\sum_{k_{1}=1}^{n}\cdot\cdot\cdot\sum_{k_{n}=1}^{n}a_{1k_{1}}b_{k_{1}\pi\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{nk_{n}}b_{k_{n}\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \sum_{k_{1}=1}^{n}\cdot\cdot\cdot\sum_{k_{n}=1}^{n}a_{1k_{1}}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{nk_{n}}\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)b_{k_{1}\pi\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{k_{n}\pi\left(n\right)}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Note that, for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2},\ldots,k_{n}\in\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,n\right\} ,$
\end_inset

 the sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)b_{k_{1}\pi\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{k_{n}\pi\left(n\right)}
\]

\end_inset

is the determinant of a matrix composed of rows 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2},\ldots,k_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by property 8, it follows that this expression vanishes unless the
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all distinct.
 In other words the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ k_{1},k_{2},\ldots,k_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 must be some permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(AB\right) & = & \sum_{\sigma\in S_{n}}a_{1\sigma\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\sigma\left(n\right)}\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\right)b_{\sigma\left(1\right)\pi\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{\sigma\left(n\right)\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\sigma\right)a_{1\sigma\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot a_{n\sigma\left(n\right)}\sum_{\pi\in S_{n}}\sgn\left(\pi\sigma^{-1}\right)b_{\sigma\left(1\right)\pi\left(1\right)}\cdot\cdot\cdot b_{\sigma\left(n\right)\pi\left(n\right)}\\
 & = & \det\left(A\right)\det\left(B\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Ex:Vandermonde"

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
Vandermonde determinant
\series default
 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the determinant defined as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{n}=\begin{vmatrix}1 & x_{1} & x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{1}^{n-1}\\
1 & x_{2} & x_{2}^{2} & \cdots & x_{2}^{n-2} & x_{2}^{n-1}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
1 & x_{n} & x_{n}^{2} & \cdots & x_{n}^{n-2} & x_{n}^{n-1}
\end{vmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Its value is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{n}=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le n}\left({x_{j}-x_{i}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Alternative formulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Donald E.
 Knuth refers to the matrix itself, and calls it Vandermonde's matrix, defining
 it compactly as 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}=x_{j}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{V}=\begin{bmatrix}x_{1} & x_{2} & \cdots & x_{n}\\
x_{1}^{2} & x_{2}^{2} & \cdots & x_{n}^{2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
x_{1}^{n} & x_{2}^{n} & \cdots & x_{n}^{n}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle \det\left({\mathbf{V}}\right)=\prod_{1\mathop\le j\mathop\le n}x_{j}\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le n}\left({x_{j}-x_{i}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

The proof follows directly from that for above and by factoring out 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 from the first column, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 from the second column, and so on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 from the last column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mirsky gives it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\begin{vmatrix}a_{1}^{n-1} & a_{1}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{1} & 1\\
a_{2}^{n-1} & a_{2}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{2} & 1\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
a_{n}^{n-1} & a_{n}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{n} & 1
\end{vmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Its value is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle D=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le n}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Soln.
 Firtst method:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can subtract row 1 from each of the other rows and leave 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n}$
\end_inset

 unchanged:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{n}=\begin{vmatrix}1 & x_{1} & x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{1}^{n-1}\\
0 & x_{2}-x_{1} & x_{2}^{2}-x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{2}^{n-2}-x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{2}^{n-1}-x_{1}^{n-1}\\
0 & x_{3}-x_{1} & x_{3}^{2}-x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{3}^{n-2}-x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{3}^{n-1}-x_{1}^{n-1}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & x_{n-1}-x_{1} & x_{n-1}^{2}-x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{n-1}^{n-2}-x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{n-1}^{n-1}-x_{1}^{n-1}\\
0 & x_{n}-x_{1} & x_{n}^{2}-x_{1}^{2} & \cdots & x_{n}^{n-2}-x_{1}^{n-2} & x_{n}^{n-1}-x_{1}^{n-1}
\end{vmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Similarly without changing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n}$
\end_inset

, we can subtract, in order, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 times column 
\begin_inset Formula $n−1$
\end_inset

 from column 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 times column 
\begin_inset Formula $n−2$
\end_inset

 from column 
\begin_inset Formula $n−1$
\end_inset

, and so on, till we subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 times column 1 from column 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first row will vanish all apart from the first element 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{11}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On all the other rows, we get, with new 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{ij}=\left({x_{i}^{j-1}-x_{1}^{j-1}}\right)-\left({x_{1}x_{i}^{j-2}-x_{1}^{j-1}}\right)=\left({x_{i}-x_{1}}\right)x_{i}^{j-2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{n}=\begin{vmatrix}1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
0 & x_{2}-x_{1} & \left({x_{2}-x_{1}}\right)x_{2} & \cdots & \left({x_{2}-x_{1}}\right)x_{2}^{n-3} & \left({x_{2}-x_{1}}\right)x_{2}^{n-2}\\
0 & x_{3}-x_{1} & \left({x_{3}-x_{1}}\right)x_{3} & \cdots & \left({x_{3}-x_{1}}\right)x_{3}^{n-3} & \left({x_{3}-x_{1}}\right)x_{3}^{n-2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & x_{n-1}-x_{1} & \left({x_{n-1}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n-1} & \cdots & \left({x_{n-1}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n-1}^{n-3} & \left({x_{n-1}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n-1}^{n-2}\\
0 & x_{n}-x_{1} & \left({x_{n}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n} & \cdots & \left({x_{n}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n}^{n-3} & \left({x_{n}-x_{1}}\right)x_{n}^{n-2}
\end{vmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

For all rows apart from the first, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th row has the common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{k}−x_{1})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we can extract all these as factors,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{n}=\prod_{k\mathop=2}^{n}\left({x_{k}-x_{1}}\right)\begin{vmatrix}1 & x_{2} & \cdots & x_{2}^{n-3} & x_{2}^{n-2}\\
1 & x_{3} & \cdots & x_{3}^{n-3} & x_{3}^{n-2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
1 & x_{n-1} & \cdots & x_{n-1}^{n-3} & x_{n-1}^{n-2}\\
1 & x_{n} & \cdots & x_{n}^{n-3} & x_{n}^{n-2}
\end{vmatrix}}
\]

\end_inset

and it can be seen that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\displaystyle V_{n}=\prod_{k\mathop=2}^{n}\left({x_{k}-x_{1}}\right)V_{n-1}}.\label{eq:Vandermonde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}=\begin{vmatrix}1 & x_{n-1}\\
1 & x_{n}
\end{vmatrix}=x_{n}-x_{n-1}
\]

\end_inset

by iterating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Vandermonde"

\end_inset

 the result follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Second method: Proof by induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{n}=\begin{vmatrix}a_{1}^{n-1} & a_{1}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{1} & 1\\
a_{2}^{n-1} & a_{2}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{2} & 1\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
a_{n}^{n-1} & a_{n}^{n-2} & \cdots & a_{n} & 1
\end{vmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

(It's written that way round to make the proof come out easier.
 This is how Mirsky derives the result.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 be the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{n}=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le n}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)},\quad n\in\mathbf{N}.
\]

\end_inset


\series bold
Base case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 is true, as this just says 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right|=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is true because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}=\begin{vmatrix}a_{1} & 1\\
a_{2} & 1
\end{vmatrix}=a_{1}-a_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\series bold
Induction hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we need to show that, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is true, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge2$
\end_inset

, then it logically follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So this is our induction hypothesis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{k}=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le k}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

Then we need to show:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{k+1}=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le k+1}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\series bold
Induction step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the determinant:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{k+1}=\begin{vmatrix}x^{k} & x^{k-1} & \cdots & x^{2} & x & 1\\
a_{2}^{k} & a_{2}^{k-1} & \cdots & a_{2}^{2} & a_{2} & 1\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
a_{k+1}^{k} & a_{k+1}^{k-1} & \cdots & a_{k+1}^{2} & a_{k+1} & 1
\end{vmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

If we expand it in terms of the first row, we can see that it is a polynomial
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 whose degree is no greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Call that polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you substitute any 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{r}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the determinant, two of its rows will be the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the value of such a determinant will be 0.
 Thus it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left({a_{2}}\right)=f\left({a_{3}}\right)=\ldots=f\left({a_{k+1}}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is divisible by each of the factors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x-a_{2},x-a_{3},\ldots,x-a_{k+1}.
\]

\end_inset

All these factors are distinct otherwise the original determinant is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left({x}\right)=C\left({x-a_{2}}\right)\left({x-a_{3}}\right)\cdots\left({x-a_{k}}\right)\left({x-a_{k+1}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

As the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is no greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Since the coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{vmatrix}a_{2}^{k-1} & \cdots & a_{2}^{2} & a_{2} & 1\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
a_{k+1}^{k-1} & \cdots & a_{k+1}^{2} & a_{k+1} & 1
\end{vmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

and, by induction hypothesis, this is equal to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle \prod_{2\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le k+1}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

so this has to be the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle f\left({x}\right)=\left({x-a_{2}}\right)\left({x-a_{3}}\right)\cdots\left({x-a_{k}}\right)\left({x-a_{k+1}}\right)\prod_{2\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le k+1}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we retrieve the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left({k}\right)\implies P\left({k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the result follows by the Principle of Mathematical Induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle V_{n}=\prod_{1\mathop\le i\mathop<j\mathop\le n}\left({a_{i}-a_{j}}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

