\begin_layout Chapter
Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we define matrices with its main operations, and we study
 various matrices formed from groups and rings.
 The English mathematician James Joseph Sylvester invented the term ``Matrix''
 in the year 1850.
 The defined matrix operations introduced by Sylvester were considered by
 Arthur Cayley in 1858, when he in his article ``A memoir on the theory
 of matrices'' for the first time considered matrices as independent algebraic
 objects .
 For us matrices form the central approach to the theory of linear algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic definitions and operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the formal definition of the matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(R,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with unity and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\in\mathbf{N}_{0}:=\mathbf{N}\cup\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A rectangular array of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[a_{ij}\right]=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & \cdots & a_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & a_{n2} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in R,\, i=1,\ldots,n,\, j=1,\ldots,m,$
\end_inset

 ie 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\times m)$
\end_inset

-matrix with entries (coefficients) in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (in short: 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\times m)$
\end_inset

-matrix over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
 We denote the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, we obtain for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

 matrices of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $0\times m,\, n\times0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $0\times0$
\end_inset

 These ``empty matrices'' we denote with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[\right]$
\end_inset

.
 They are needed in some proofs for technical reasons.
 However, when we later speak of algebraic structures as matrix groups or
 rings, we will always mean matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m≥1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The zero matrix in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $0_{n,m}$
\end_inset

 or simply 0, is the matrix is ​all of whose entries are equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m$
\end_inset

, then we call 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 a square matrix.
 The entries 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ii}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\emph on
diagonal
\emph default
 entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
identity matrix
\emph default
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}:=\left[\delta_{ij}\right]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{ij}=\begin{cases}
1 & \textrm{if }i=j,\\
0 & \textrm{if }i\neq j,
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

is the so-called 
\emph on
Kronecker-Delta Function
\emph default
.
 If it is clear what 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is, we also write 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 we define 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}:=\left[\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th 
\emph on
row
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a_{i1},a_{i2},\ldots,a_{im}\right]$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\in R^{1,m},i=1,\ldots,n,$
\end_inset

 where we use commas for separating the entries for visual clarity.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th 
\emph on
column
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}a_{1j}\\
a_{2j}\\
\vdots\\
a_{nj}
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{n,1},\quad j=1,\ldots,m.
\]

\end_inset

The rows and columns of a matrix are thus again matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, if we are given the 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\times m)$
\end_inset

-matrices 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{i}=\left[a_{i1},a_{i2}\ldots,a_{im}\right]\text{\in}R^{1,m},\quad i=1,\ldots,n,
\]

\end_inset

 we can form from these the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
\vdots\\
a_{n}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & \cdots & a_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & a_{n2} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{n,m}.
\]

\end_inset

 Here we omit the square brackets around each row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly from the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\times1)$
\end_inset

-matrices
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{j}:=\begin{bmatrix}a_{1j}\\
a_{2j}\\
\vdots\\
a_{nj}
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{n,1},\quad j=1,\ldots,m
\]

\end_inset

we can form the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[a_{1},a_{2}\ldots,a_{m}\right]=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & \cdots & a_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & a_{n2} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{n,m}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1},n_{2},m_{1},m_{2}\in\mathbf{N}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}\in R^{n_{i},m_{j}},i,j=1,2,$
\end_inset

 we can form from these four matrices, the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}A_{11} & A_{12}\\
A_{21} & A_{22}
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{n_{1}+n_{2},m_{1}+m_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

 The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are then called 
\emph on
Blocks
\emph default
 of the Blockmatrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algebra of Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now define four different operations with matrices and begin the 
\emph on
Addition
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\,:\, R^{n,m}\times R^{n,m}\longrightarrow R^{n,m},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A,\, B)\longmapsto A+B\,:=\left[a_{ij}+b_{i,j}\right].
\]

\end_inset

 The addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 so done entry-wise, based on the addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the addition is only defined for matrices of equal size.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Multiplication
\emph default
 of two matrices is defined as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\star\,:\, R^{n,m}\times R^{m,s}\longrightarrow R^{n,s}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A,\, B)\longmapsto A\star B=\left[c_{ij}\right],\quad c_{ij}\,:=\sum_{k=1}^{m}a_{ik}b_{kj}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entry 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 is produced by the successive multiplication and summation of the entries
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in the definition of the entries 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 no sign is used for the multiplicative combination of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 This follows the usual convention, the multiplication sign simply is omitted
 if it is clear as to what multiplication is.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to define the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

, the number of columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must obviously be equal to the number of rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rule of thumb is 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 times the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can illustrate this as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
\quad & \overbrace{\begin{bmatrix}b_{11} & \cdots & \quad b_{1j} & \cdots & b_{1s}\\
\vdots &  & \quad\vdots\\
b_{m1} & \cdots & \quad b_{mj} & \cdots & b_{ms}
\end{bmatrix}}^{B}\\
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots a &  & \vdots\\
a_{i1} & \cdots & a_{im}\\
\vdots &  & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{bmatrix}}_{A} & \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} & \phantom{\cdots} &  & \phantom{\cdots} & \phantom{b_{1s}}\\
 &  & \downarrow\\
\longrightarrow &  & \quad c_{ij}\\
\\
\\
\end{bmatrix}}_{C}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

Note that the matrix multiplication is not commutative in general!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
For the matrices
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3\\
4 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,3},\quad B=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
-1 & 1\\
0 & 0\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{3,2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\star B=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
2 & -2\\
2 & -2
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,2}.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula $B\star A\in\mathbf{Z}^{3,3}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B\neq B\star A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-commutativity exists even when 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\star A$
\end_inset

 have the same order as the following example shows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
1 & 2\\
0 & 3
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,2},\quad B=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
4 & 0\\
5 & 6
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,2}
\]

\end_inset

then the two products are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\star B=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
14 & 12\\
15 & 18
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}\quad\textrm{and}\quad B\star A=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
4 & 8\\
5 & 28
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the lack of commutativity of matrix multiplication it has certain
 important properties.
 In particular associativity and distributivity apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Lemma:Matrix-Mult"

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $A,F\in R^{n,m},\ B,G\in R^{m,l}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in R^{l,k}$
\end_inset

 the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star\left(B\star C\right)=\left(A\star B\right)\star C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(2) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A+F\right)\star B=A\star B+F\star B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(3) 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star\left(B+G\right)=A\star B+A\star G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(4) 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}\star A=A\star I_{m}=A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We shall prove only (1): Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m},\ B\in R^{m,l}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in R^{l,k}$
\end_inset

.
 Set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[d_{ij}\right]=\left(A\star B\right)\star C\quad\textrm{and}\quad\left[e_{ij}\right]=A\star\left(B\star C\right).
\]

\end_inset

By definition of matrix multiplication and the distributive and associative
 laws in the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
