\begin_layout Standard
We accept the following transition rule: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No damage: (or remain in )
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 in the following year move a class higher.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A refundable damage: In the following year a class back (or stay in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More than one claim: In the following year (back) in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the insurer must assess the likelihood that an insured person who is
 is in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i}$
\end_inset

 in this year, changes in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{j}$
\end_inset

 in the following year.
 This probability we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose for simplicity that the probability (exactly) of any claim for
 each insured is 0.1 (ie 10%) and the probability of two or more claims is
 0.05 (5%).
 (In practice, the insurers decide these probabilities, and of course, depend
 on the respective classes.) Consider for example the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{11}=0.15,\, p_{12}=0.85,\, p_{13}=0.00,\: p_{14}=0.00.
\]

\end_inset

 Whoever is this year in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

, remains in this class after one or more damage.
 The probability of this happening is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{11}=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A person in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 is, with probability 0.85 has no claim and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{12}=0.85$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, there is no possibility of a person in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 this year moves to one of the classes 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 in the next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can arrange the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij},\, i,j=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

, in a numbering scheme - a matrix.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\begin{bmatrix}p_{11} & p_{12} & p_{13} & p_{14}\\
p_{21} & p_{22} & p_{23} & p_{24}\\
p_{31} & p_{32} & p_{33} & p_{34}\\
p_{41} & p_{42} & p_{43} & p_{44}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0.15 & 0.85 & 0.00 & 0.00\\
0.15 & 0.00 & 0.85 & 0.00\\
0.05 & 0.10 & 0.00 & 0.85\\
0.05 & 0.00 & 0.10 & 0.85
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

All entries of this matrix are non-negative real numbers and the sum of
 all entries in each line is equal to 1.00.
 Such a matrix is called a 
\emph on
stochastic matrix
\emph default
.
 The analysis of the properties of such matrices is an important topic of
 linear algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the insurer has this year following distribution of customers in
 the four claims categories: 40% of customers are in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

, 30% in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

, 20% in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 10% in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the distribution of customers can be represented by a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{0}=\begin{bmatrix}0.4 & 0.3 & 0.2 & 0.1\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

and the distribution next year is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{0}\star P & = & \begin{bmatrix}0.4 & 0.3 & 0.2 & 0.1\end{bmatrix}\star\begin{bmatrix}0.15 & 0.85 & 0.00 & 0.00\\
0.15 & 0.00 & 0.85 & 0.00\\
0.05 & 0.10 & 0.00 & 0.85\\
0.05 & 0.00 & 0.10 & 0.85
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & = & \begin{bmatrix}0.12 & 0.36 & 0.265 & 0.255\end{bmatrix}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Why is that? As an example, consider the entry (1,4): it is calculated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}=0.4\times0.00+0.3\times0.00+0.2\times0.85+0.1\times0.85=0.255.
\]

\end_inset

This entry represents the percentage of customers that in the next year
 will be in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 (these are therefore 25.5%).
 Those who are this year in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 and class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

 , may in following year not come into 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

, so we multiply the output distributions 0.4 and 0.3 with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{14}=0.00$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{24}=0.00$
\end_inset

.
 Those in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 will be in class 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 in the following year with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{34}=0.85$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{44}=0.85$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 This results is the products 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\times0.85$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1\times0.85$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One sees now the customer distribution after 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 years is given by the formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}=p_{0}\star P^{n},\quad n=0,1,2,\ldots
\]

\end_inset

The formula is also valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{0}=I_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

