\begin_layout Section
Columns and Rows of a Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us introduce 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\e_{1},\ldots,\e_{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{m,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 row vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\u_{1}^{T},\ldots,\u_{n}^{T}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{1,n}$
\end_inset

  by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\e_{1}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{bmatrix},\,\e_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\
1\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{bmatrix},\ldots,\e_{m}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{m,1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\u_{1}^{T}=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\end{bmatrix},\ldots,\u_{n}^{T}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & \cdots & 1\end{bmatrix}\in R^{1,n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\u_{k}=\e_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[a_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 we have for the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A\star\e_{k} & = & \begin{bmatrix}a_{1k}\\
a_{2k}\\
\vdots\\
a_{nk}
\end{bmatrix}=a_{1k}\cdot\u_{1}+\cdots+a_{nk}\cdot\u_{n}:=\c_{k},\\
\u_{k}^{T}\star A & = & \begin{bmatrix}a_{k1} & a_{k2} & \cdots & a_{km}\end{bmatrix}=a_{k1}\cdot\e_{1}^{T}+\cdots+a_{km}\cdot\e_{m}^{T}:=\r_{k}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This shows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th column of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\u_{i}$
\end_inset

's with the coefficients from the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\e_{i}^{T}$
\end_inset

's with coefficients picked up from the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider the multiplication of two matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m},\, B\in R^{m,l},\, C\in R^{l,n}$
\end_inset

.
 First consider the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\e$
\end_inset

's and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\u$
\end_inset

's are to be interpreted in the appropriate dimensions.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,\ldots,l$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(A\star B\right)\star\e_{k} & = & A\star\left(B\star\e_{k}\right)\\
 & = & A\star\b_{k}\qquad(\textrm{where }\b_{k}\textrm{ is the }k\textrm{-th column of }B)\\
 & = & A\star\left(b_{1k}\cdot\u_{1}+\cdots+b_{mk}\cdot\u_{m}\right)\\
 & = & b_{1k}\cdot A\star\u_{1}+\cdots+b_{mk}\cdot A\star\u_{m}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\emph on
The columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 are linear combinations of the coulumns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th column being a linear combination with coefficients from the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,\ldots,l$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\u_{k}^{T}\star\left(C\star A\right) & = & \left(\u_{k}^{T}\star C\right)\star A\\
 & = & \r_{k}\star A\qquad(\textrm{where }\b_{k}\textrm{ is the }k\textrm{-th row of }C)\\
 & = & \left(c_{k1}\cdot\e_{1}^{T}+\cdots+c_{kn}\cdot\e_{n}^{T}\right)\star A\\
 & = & c_{k1}\cdot\e_{1}^{T}\star A+\cdots+c_{kn}\cdot\e_{n}^{T}\star A.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\emph on
The rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $C\star A$
\end_inset

 are linear combinations of the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row being a linear combination with coefficients from the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

.
 Find a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 results in a matrix in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 which is an exchange of coulumns 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with all the other columns remaining same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Soln.

\series default
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 must be in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{m,m}$
\end_inset

.
 From the discussion above applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 we must have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{ij}\star\e_{k} & = & \e_{k}\quad\text{if }k\neq i,j\\
P_{ij}\star\e_{i} & = & \e_{j}\\
P_{ij}\star\e_{j} & = & \e_{i}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is given by (for 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{ij}=\begin{bmatrix}\e_{1}, & \cdots, & \e_{j}, & \cdots & \e_{i}, & \cdots, & \e_{m}\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

