\begin_layout Section
Matrix Groups and Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we examine algebraic structures for matrices and by the
 manner in which they are built from the defined operations.
 We begin with the addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Thm:Matrix-Group"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(R^{n,m},+)$
\end_inset

is a commutative group with neutral element 
\begin_inset Formula $0_{n,m}$
\end_inset

 (zero matrix) and for 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[a_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 the inverse element 
\begin_inset Formula $-A:=\left[-a_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

.
 (Instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+(-B)$
\end_inset

 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $A-B$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
associativity:
\series default
 is true because of associativity in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(A+B\right)+C & = & \left[a_{ij}+b_{ij}\right]+\left[c_{ij}\right]\\
 & = & \left[\left(a_{ij}+b_{ij}\right)+c_{ij}\right]\\
 & = & \left[a_{ij}+\left(b_{ij}+c_{ij}\right)\right]\\
 & = & A+\left(B+C\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\series bold
identity:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $0_{n,m}$
\end_inset

 plays the role of identity since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A+0_{n,m}=\left[a_{ij}+0\right]=A=0_{n,m}+A.
\]

\end_inset


\series bold
inverse:
\series default
 the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-A:=\left[-a_{ij}\right]$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A+\left(-A\right)=\left[a_{ij}+\left(-a_{ij}\right)\right]=0_{n,m}=\left(-A\right)+A.
\]

\end_inset


\series bold
commutativity:
\series default
 this follows from commutativity in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A+B=\left[a_{ij}+b_{ij}\right]=\left[b_{ij}\right]+\left[a_{ij}\right]=B+A.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Remark.

\series default
 Because of Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Transpose"

\end_inset

 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $A\longmapsto A^{T}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism (in fact an isomorphism) of the groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R^{n,m},+\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R^{m,n},+\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we come to the question of whether and when matrices are invertiblewith
 respect to multiplication .
 To have a multiplicative inverse for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 means existence of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B=I=B\star A$
\end_inset

.
 For this to even be possible we must have that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be square to begin with.
 The definition of invertible matrices is thus limited to the square matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
invertible
\emph default
, if there exists a matrx 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B=I_{n}=B\star A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not all matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 are invertible.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0\right]$
\end_inset

 is not invertible if 
\begin_inset Formula $1\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 For a more interesting example consider a ring where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\neq0$
\end_inset

 then the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\in R^{2,2}
\]

\end_inset

is not invertible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to keep in mind that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is invertible then the inverse must also be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for example for the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
0 & 2
\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,2}
\]

\end_inset

there is a matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\begin{bmatrix}\begin{array}{rr}
1 & -\frac{1}{2}\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

with the property 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\star B=I_{2}=B\star A
\]

\end_inset

but 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $B\not\in\mathbf{Z}^{2,2}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
though 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathbf{Q}^{2,2}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}^{2,2}$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also important to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset

 has non-trivial zero divisors.
 i.e., there are matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, for which there is a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in R^{n,n}\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B=0$
\end_inset

 there.
 For example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2,2}$
\end_inset

 consider the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}0 & 1\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\star\begin{bmatrix}0 & 1\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Here, then, in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, although 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this identity also holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 The existence of non-trivial zero divisors shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset

 can not be an integral domain, even if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field (this also follows from the noncommutativity of matrix multiplicatio
n).
 However, the following theorem holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R^{n,n},+,\star\right)$
\end_inset

 is a (non-commutative) ring with the identity element 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We have already shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $(R^{n,n},+)$
\end_inset

 is a commutative group (Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Thm:Matrix-Group"

\end_inset

 ).
 The other properties (associativity, distributivity and identity element)
 follow from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Transpose"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Remark.

\series default
 It follows that the inverse of an invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined.
 This matrix is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For invertible matrices the following results holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Lemma:Matrix-Inverse"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,\, B\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 be invertible matrices.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

 is invertible and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A^{T}\right)^{-1}=\left(A^{-1}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(2) 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 is invertible with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A\star B\right)^{-1}=B^{-1}\star A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(1) We have from property (4) of Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Transpose"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(A^{-1}\right)^{T}\star A^{T} & = & \left(A\star A^{-1}\right)^{T}\\
 & = & I_{n}^{T}=I_{n}\\
 & = & A^{-1}\star A\\
 & = & \left(A^{-1}\star A\right)^{T}\\
 & = & A^{T}\star\left(A^{-1}\right)^{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A^{-1}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(2) This is a standard fact in semi-groups.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(B^{-1}\star A^{-1}\right)\star\left(A\star B\right) & = & B^{-1}\star\left(A\star A^{-1}\star B\right)\\
 & = & B^{-1}\star B\\
 & = & I_{n}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

similarly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A\star B\right)\star\left(B^{-1}\star A^{-1}\right)=I_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we show that the set of invertible matrices form a group with respect
 to multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Thm:Group-of-Invertible-Matrices"

\end_inset

The set of invertible matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 with the binary operation of matrix multiplication forms a (non-commutative)
 group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The closure of the set of invertible matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 with respect to multiplication has already been shown in (2) in Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Matrix-Inverse"

\end_inset

, and the associativity of multiplication in Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Matrix-Mult"

\end_inset

.
 The neutral element of this set is 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, each member of the set, it is invertible, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{-1})^{-1}=A$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also invertible so belongs to the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The group of invertible matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

, will be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

 (``
\begin_inset Formula $GL$
\end_inset

'' stands for ``general linear group'').
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let  
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[a_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(1) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
upper triangular
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
lower triangular
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j>i$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

 is an upper triangular matrix).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(2) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\emph on
diagonal matrix
\emph default
, when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is both an upper and a lower triangular matrix.
 We write for simplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\diag\left(a_{11},\ldots,a_{nn}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We wish to these special sets of matrices for their group properties.
 We begin with the invertible upper and lower triangular matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Thm:Group-of-Triangular-Matrices"

\end_inset

The set of invertible upper triangular matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 and the invertible lower triangular matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 respectively forms a (non-commutative) subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We prove the assertion only for invertible upper triangular matrices.
 The proof for invertible lower triangular is analogous.
 To show that the invertible upper triangular with the matrix multiplication
 form a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

, we verify the three properties of a group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The identity matriox 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible upper triangular matrix, so the set of invertible upper
 triangular matrices is a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now we show that for any two invertible upper triangular matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 the product 
\begin_inset Formula $C=A\star B$
\end_inset

 is an invertible upper triangular matrix.
 The invertibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left[c_{ij}\right]$
\end_inset

 follows from (2) in Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Lemma:Matrix-Inverse"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c_{ij} & = & \sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}b_{kj}\qquad\textrm{(here }b_{kj}=0\textrm{ for }k>j\textrm{)}\\
 & = & \sum_{k=1}^{j}a_{ik}b_{kj}\qquad\textrm{(here }a_{ik}=0\textrm{ for }k=1,\ldots,j,\textrm{ if }i>j\textrm{)}\\
 & = & 0.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Next we show that for a given upper triangular invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also an upper triangular matrix.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 the statement is trivial, Therefore, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=\left[c_{ij}\right]$
\end_inset

, then the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star A^{-1}=I_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be write the form of a system of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equations as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
0 & a_{22} & \cdots & \cdots & a_{2n}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & a_{nn}
\end{bmatrix}\star\begin{bmatrix}c_{1j}\\
c_{2j}\\
\vdots\\
c_{nj}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\delta_{1j}\\
\delta_{2j}\\
\vdots\\
\delta_{nj}
\end{bmatrix},\quad j=1,\ldots,n.\label{eq:2.3.1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker delta function.
 We have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We claim (and show inductively): The diagonal entries 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ii}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are invertible and for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n,n-1\ldots,1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{ij}=a_{ii}^{-1}\left(\delta_{ij}-\sum_{l=i+1}^{n}a_{il}c_{lj}\right),\quad j=1,\ldots,n.\label{eq:2.3.2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(Note that in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.2"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n$
\end_inset

, we have the empty sum which by convention is 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From the last equation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.1"

\end_inset

 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{nn}c_{nj}=\delta_{nj},\quad j=1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset

In particular for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=n$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{nn}c_{nn}=1=c_{nn}a_{nn}$
\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{nn}$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 Here we have used the commutativity of the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 It then follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{nj}=a_{nn}^{-1}\delta_{nj}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.2"

\end_inset

 is established for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now suppose that our assertion for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n,\ldots,k+1$
\end_inset

 holds, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le k\le n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1\le i\le n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

.
 In other words: The rows 
\begin_inset Formula $i=n,...,k+1$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are in ``upper triangular form.'' To prove the statement, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=k$
\end_inset

, we consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th row in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.1"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{kk}c_{kj}+a_{k,k+1}c_{k+1,j}+\cdots+a_{kn}c_{nj}=\delta_{kj},\quad j=1,\ldots,n.\label{eq:2.3.3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $j=k\,(<n)$
\end_inset

 we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{kk}c_{kk}+a_{k,k+1}c_{k+1,k}+\cdots+a_{kn}c_{nk}=1.
\]

\end_inset

By the induction hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k+1,k}=\cdots=c_{nk}=0,$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{kk}c_{kk}=1=c_{kk}a_{kk}$
\end_inset

 where we have used the commutativity of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{kk}$
\end_inset

 is invertible with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{kk}=a_{kk}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 It now follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.3"

\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{kj}=a_{kk}^{-1}\left(\delta_{kj}-a_{k,k+1}c_{k+1,j}-\cdots-a_{kn}c_{nj}\right),\quad j=1,\ldots,n
\]

\end_inset

which is 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2.3.2"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=k$
\end_inset

.
 If further 
\begin_inset Formula $k>j$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{kj}=0$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k+1,j}=\cdots=c_{nj}=0$
\end_inset

 it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{kj}=0.$
\end_inset

 The proof is complete by induction.
\end_layout

