\begin_layout Proof
The invertible diagonal matrices of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 form a non-empty subset of invertible upper (or lower) triangular matrices
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

; in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible diagonal matrix in this set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left[a_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left[b_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

, are two invertible diagonal matrices, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\star B$
\end_inset

 is invertible and due to the commutativity in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A\star B & = & \diag\left(a_{11}b_{11},\ldots,a_{nn}b_{nn}\right)\\
 & = & \diag\left(b_{11}a_{11},\ldots,b_{nn}a_{nn}\right)=B\star A.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 This shows closure and commutativity of multiplication in the set of invertible
 diagonal matrices.
 We also know from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Thm:Group-of-Triangular-Matrices"

\end_inset

 that the inverse of an invertible upper (lower) triangular matrix, is an
 upper (lower) triangular matrix.
 So is 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible diagonal matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is both an upper and lower triangular matrix, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also a diagonal matrix.
\end_layout

