\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Def:Permutation-Matrix"

\end_inset

A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
permutation matrix
\emph default
 if in each row and each column of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 exactly one entry is 1 and all other entries are 0.
 The term ``permutation'' means ``exchange''.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Multiplying a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 with a permutation matrix from the left or from the right, interchanges
 the rows columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 For example for,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix},\qquad M=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3\\
4 & 5 & 6\\
7 & 8 & 9
\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbf{Z}^{3,3}
\]

\end_inset

the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\star M=\begin{bmatrix}7 & 8 & 9\\
4 & 5 & 6\\
1 & 2 & 3
\end{bmatrix},\quad\textrm{and}\quad M\star P=\begin{bmatrix}3 & 2 & 1\\
6 & 5 & 4\\
9 & 8 & 7
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Thm:Group-of-Permutations"

\end_inset

The set of permutation matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

, w.r.t the matrix multiplication is a (non-commutative) subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is a permutation matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is invertible and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}=P^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let  
\begin_inset Formula $P=\left[p_{ij}\right]\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 be a permutation matrix, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $P\star P^{T}=C=\left[c_{ij}\right]$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{ij}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}p_{ik}p_{jk}=\delta_{ij}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C=I_{n}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{T}\star P=I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The permutation matrices therefore form a (non-empty) subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(R)$
\end_inset

 and the inverse of any permutation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the transposed matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{T}$
\end_inset

, which also is a permutation matrix by definition.
 Finally it remains to show that the product of two permutation matrices
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1},P_{2}\in R^{n,n}$
\end_inset

 is also a permutation matrix.
 This can be seen immediately from the fact that there is exactly one entry
 equal to 1 in each row and column of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 and all other entries are 0.
\end_layout

