\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many applications, one is interested in whether a (square) matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible and you may well wish to compute the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 or solve a linear systems of equations with the coefficient matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In this chapter, we will develop a systematic method that for an invertible
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, which is defined over a field, the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is obtained as a product of the so-called elementary matrices.
 If these elementary matrices from are multiplied on the left of the matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, one therefore obtains the identity matrix.
 Applied to a non-invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not result in the identity matrix, but results in a matrix, ,that
 is ``as close to'' to the unit matrix, in a certain sense.
 The term rank of matrices is motivated, which in linear algebra is of great
 importance and occurs frequently occur in later chapters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Elementary Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with identity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the identity matrix and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\e_{i}$
\end_inset

be the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=\left[\e_{1},\ldots,\e_{n}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\, j\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le i,\, j\le n$
\end_inset

 we define the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{ij}:=\left[0,\ldots,0,\underbrace{\ \e_{i}\ }_{\text{Column }j},0,\ldots,0\right]
\]

\end_inset

i.e., the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i,\, j\right)$
\end_inset

 element of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is 1, all other elements are 0.
 In the following three definitions of 
\emph on
Elementary Matrices
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will denote natural numbers between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

 we define the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{ij}=\left[\e_{1},\ldots,\e_{i-1},\e_{j},\e_{i+1},\ldots,\e_{j-1},\e_{i},\e_{j+1},\ldots,\e_{n}\right]\in R^{n,n}.\label{eq:permutation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is a permutation matrix.
 It has the property that on left multiplication on a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

 results in the exchange of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in R$
\end_inset

 we define the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{i}\left(\lambda\right):=\left[\e_{1},\ldots,\e_{i-1},\lambda\e_{i},\e_{i+1},\ldots,\e_{n}\right]\in R^{n,n}.\label{eq:Mult-by-lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th column of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\e_{i}.$
\end_inset

 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th diagonal element 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and all other diagonal elements 1.
 Multiplying a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in R^{n,m}$
\end_inset

